05033nam a22006015i 9780822391142DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223911427 a10.1515/97808223911422doi  a(DE-B1597)554272  a(OCoLC)1224278732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDD76b.M545 2009 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a320.540943083/51 aMiller-Idriss, Cynthia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlood and Culture :bYouth, Right-Wing Extremism, and National Belonging in Contemporary Germany‹br› /cCynthia Miller-Idriss; ed. by George Steinmetz, Julia Adams. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics, History, and Culture : 3000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Citizenship and National Belonging as Cultural Practices -- tChapter 1. Who Belongs to the Nation? -- tChapter 2. Being and Becoming in Germany -- tChapter 3. Germany’s Forbidden Fruit: National Pride and National Taboos -- tChapter 4. Raising the Right Wing: Educators’ Struggle to Confront the Radical Right -- tChapter 5. Teaching and Unteaching National Identity -- tChapter 6. Blood, Culture, Birthplace -- tChapter 7. Generational Change and the Re-imagining of Nations -- tAppendix a. Overview of the Case Studies -- tAppendix b. Methodological Overview -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past decade, immigration and globalization have significantly altered Europe’s cultural and ethnic landscape, foregrounding questions of national belonging. In Blood and Culture, Cynthia Miller-Idriss provides a rich ethnographic analysis of how patterns of national identity are constructed and transformed across generations. Drawing on research she conducted at German vocational schools between 1999 and 2004, Miller-Idriss examines how the working-class students and their middle-class, college-educated teachers wrestle with their different views about citizenship and national pride. The cultural and demographic trends in Germany are broadly indicative of those underway throughout Europe, yet the country’s role in the Second World War and the Holocaust makes national identity, and particularly national pride, a difficult issue for Germans. Because the vocational-school teachers are mostly members of a generation that came of age in the 1960s and 1970s and hold their parents’ generation responsible for National Socialism, many see national pride as symptomatic of fascist thinking. Their students, on the other hand, want to take pride in being German.Miller-Idriss describes a new understanding of national belonging emerging among young Germans—one in which cultural assimilation takes precedence over blood or ethnic heritage. Moreover, she argues that teachers’ well-intentioned, state-sanctioned efforts to counter nationalist pride often create a backlash, making radical right-wing groups more appealing to their students. Miller-Idriss argues that the state’s efforts to shape national identity are always tempered and potentially transformed as each generation reacts to the official conception of what the nation “ought” to be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCitizenshipzGermany. 0aNational characteristics, German. 0aNationalismzGermany. 0aRight-wing extremistszGermany. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Julia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSteinmetz, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press 